\section{Experimental Results \& Analysis}

\section{Experimental Results}

\subsection{Counter Experiment 1}

\shadetable{|c|c|c|}{Lock type & Raw Count & Speedup}
{Overhead - 100 MS - 5 run average}{  
none   &  25422244   &  -   \\
CLH   &  5618229   &  0.22  \\
TAS   &  5277035   &  0.20  \\
TASB   &  4660841   &  0.18  \\
mutex   &  3779035   &  0.14  \\
ALOCK   &  1955261   &  0.07  
}{tab:test1}


We can see in Table~1 that the CLH lock displayed the lowest overhead
for single threaded time-based schemes. This is not what I
predicted. I assumed that the increased work required to sort out the
linked list would outweigh any benefits in terms of contention.
Considering there is a single thread attempting to gain control of the
lock, I still do not have a solid explanation for this result.

\subsection{Counter Experument 2}

\shadetable{|c|c|c|}{Lock type & Raw Count & Speedup}
{Overhead - 262144 count total - 5 run average}{  
none    &  1100  &    -  \\
CLH     &  4734  &  0.23  \\
TAS     &  5089  &  0.21  \\
TASB    &  5739  &  0.19  \\
mutex   &  7052  &  0.15  \\
ALOCK   &  13689 &  0.08  
}{tab:test1}

Again, we see nearly identicle results with the single threaded
functions, even though the data in table two was the result of a
work-based scheme.  This is concurrent with my hypothesis that
``Because both this and the previous test are functionally
indesdinguishable (as far as I can tell) tests of throughput, the
performance differences between implementations will be the same as in
Experiment~1.''

\subsection{Counter Experiment 3}

I found that the optimal delay settings for the exponential backoff
lock were with a minimum of 256 $\mu$s and a maximum of 2056$\mu$s.
However, I do not present these numbers with confidence, because the
margin between the optimal count using these parameters was not great,
and in successive runs, the optimal parameters found were subject to
change.  Nevertheless, using this setting, I obtained the following data.

\figH {../plots/experiment3.png}{Experiment 3}{LABEL}{1}        

We can see that for the time based threads, the {\tt TASB} lock was
most successful at scaling, while the {\tt ALOCK} performed the worst
with scaling. I predicted that the {\tt ALOCK} would outperform both
the {\tt TAS(B)} locks and the {\tt CLH} lock because of its ability
to spread the contention while limiting the overhead.  However, it may
be that there is a caching issure preventing it from seeing this
performance.

\subsection{Counter Experiment 4}

Althought the {\tt TASB} lock demonstrates similar performance in a
work-based scheme, as show in Figure~2, the other locks are faced with
the scaling penalty with relatively lower thread counts.  I suspect
that the general steeper performance curve is due the fairness of the
lock. Because we are waiting for each thread to perform a given number
of operates after claiming the lock, an unlucky thread might have to
wait untill all of the others are finished to begin its work.

\figH {../plots/experiment4.png}{Experiment 4}{LABEL}{1}        

\subsection{Counter Experiment 5}

Figure~\ref{LABEL5} demonstrates the relationship between the
throughput of each lock and the thread fairness.  As expected, the
standard deviation of thread counts from the test and set locks are
much higher than those of the other locks. This is because there is no
garuntee that a thread who attempted to acquire the lock first
actually does so. However, we see a very very small standard deviation
for the {\tt ALOCK} and {\tt CLH} queue lock. This is because these
locks line up threads as they attempt to acquire the lock.  The data
suggests that the test and set locks are about 4 times less fair.
However, we can visually acknowledge the tradeoff between the fairness
of the {\tt CLH} or even the mutex over the throughput of the {\tt
TASB}

\figH {../plots/experiment5.png}{Experiment 5}{LABEL5}{1}        

